As far as not catching checked exceptions goes, this is actually possible in the Java language as well since the language allows throwing a generic type parameter.  It&#x27;s pretty difficult to do by accident though, and does at least give a compile warning.<p><pre><code>    public class Dangerous {

        public static void main (String ... args) {
            Dangerous.<RuntimeException>throwUnchecked(new IOException(&quot;Forgot to catch me!&quot;));
        }

        static <T extends Exception> void throwUnchecked(Exception e) throws T{
            throw (T) e;
        }
    }</code></pre>
